<subSubSection id="77738A2D351F07624C94C8F0B6FFADEA" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="36C21D4E089D92AFE7CD3BE95BDC88D9" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E5EC3A2F5FB6C5249BBF7C6AEB50A433" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">
Latin adjective 
<taxonomicName id="A733852BB30569BE634EB74A5C3FA367" lsidName="angustus" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" rank="species" species="angustus">angustus</taxonomicName>
, meaning narrow. This is the most elongated species in the genus in the Afrotropical region.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7060298E5FC8F7828E091F69CC130EC0" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="67A5857F1316550FBBA050EA6AE49EF9" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">Distribution and biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B5E9531497FA9B915D7F8291D9AB4155" pageId="2" pageNumber="35">
Only known from the type locality. It was taken together with 
<taxonomicName id="24B085D99EB89897B0B29DA3774FE2DE" genus="M." lsidName="M. camerunus" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" rank="species" species="camerunus">M. camerunus</taxonomicName>
(Eggers, 1919) under thick bark of a fallen 
<taxonomicName id="C54C315FAC48EE37CF017EA9DF9E740B" class="Gastropoda" family="Ficidae" genus="Ficus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ficus" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Ficus</taxonomicName>
tree. Both species used entrance holes made by 
<taxonomicName id="61A68A61EC380BDE06AAC11EEEEF696C" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Stereocaulaceae" genus="Xyleborus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Xyleborus principalis" order="Lecanorales" pageId="2" pageNumber="35" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="principalis">Xyleborus principalis</taxonomicName>
Eichhoff, 1878.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
